AGi - A new front has been opened in the Ukrainian conflict on who will control the country's mineral resources, after the end of the fights. With great expectations on the proceeds, which could however be disappointed. US President, Donald Trump, announced he wanted "the equivalent of $500 billion in rare lands" >while the homologue in Kiev, Volodymyr Zelensky, expressed his dissent, warning that he would not "sign something ten generations of Ukrainians will pay later". But there is a small problem in this discussion about the billions, if not trillions, which would come from the minerals of Ukraine: In reality this supposed wealth is not so rich.
Technically speaking, rare lands are 17 of the 118 elements of the periodic table: scandio, ittrio, lantanio, cerio, praseodimio, neodimio, promezio, samario, europio, gadolinio, terbio, disprosio, olmio, erbio, heel, itterbio and lutezio. All precious. "Ukraine, except for a little scan, basically has no rare lands, so it would be more appropriate to talk about agreement with the U.S. for minerals and critical resources," explains in an interview with AGI Gianclaudio Torlizzi, founder of the T-Commodity consulting company and advisor of the Minister of Defense on rare raw materials and materials. Torlizzi draws attention to the fact that Ukraine "has a decent wealth, but it is not a mining champion such as the Congo for cobalt or Chile for copper." According to the expert, the confusion about rare lands can be explained "on the one hand with the choice of the Ukrainians of limestone a bit 'the hand on this aspect in order to increase the interest of the West towards them and on the other with the used a little simplistic faction by Trump that under this category makes to fall a little ' everything".
&nbsp;
<div </div
&nbsp;
<h2> The riches of Ukraine
The understanding of the minerals that tomorrow should be finalized to the White House as part of the visit of Zelensky, "is about titanium, of which Ukraine is sixth producer worldwide and which represents the greatest attraction for its use in the defense industry, coal and gas deposits and iron minerals", emphasizes Torlizzi. Ukraine, moreover, has graphite, which is not a rare land, but a strategic mineral and lithium, fundamental for the battery industry> and the business of electric vehicles, but of which we have in abundance throughout the world and whose most promising deposits are located in the region of Zaporizhzhia, partially under Russian control.
What Ukraine is really rich is iron minerals, natural gas and coal, discovered by Welsh John Hughes in the 19th century in the Donets River valley, in Donbass. The same regional capital Donetsk in the past was called Hughesovka in his honor. The problem is that all these unused gas reserves are located right along the current lines of the front and many coal mines are under Russian control and are since 2014. The possibilities for these deposits are very small. "The real negotiation in this area will be between Moscow and Washington," which according to the analyst, "the strategic resources of the country are already being discarded >"
For Torlizzi, on rare lands "the basic confusion is that they associate themselves improperly to so-called critical minerals", while being two very different things: rare lands are a group of 17 elements well specified in the periodic table and used in small quantities in semiconductors, and critical minerals are important raw materials from the economic point of view and present a high risk in terms of supply. Also on the concept of 'raro' we have to make clear: "The rare lands are not at all rare, Italy itself has deposits, the true 'rarity' is their refinement that serves to make them commercial," the expert says.
"This is a process that requires a lot of energy and water and is very polluting, for this reason the West over the years has delocalized it more and more in China, which today is to control more than 90% of the refining of these elements globally." The new Washington posture on Ukraine is part of a broader strategy: "In this Second Cold War the gap with Beijing on raw materials became a pillar of American foreign policy, pursued even more aggressively than the past." This explains the American attention to Greenland, "which has a great mining availability and Canada which is a world-wide producer of critical metals," concludes Torlizzi.
